{"edits":[{"changed_fields":["claim","mechanism"],"content":"{\"claim\":\"Harness strictly beats self-consistency only when the critic uses a likelihood ratio test that conditions on candidate agreement geometry, vetoing when the intra-set disagreement entropy exceeds an adaptive threshold.\",\"mechanism\":\"Binary veto fails because it cannot distinguish a wrong-but-confident majority from a correct-but-split one. If the critic computes the entropy H of agreement among the k candidates and vetoes when H > tau_adaptive(tau_base + alpha * base_error), the harness selectively filters ambiguous wrong-majority sets while preserving unanimous correct sets. The strict advantage regime exists when the entropy distribution of wrong-majority sets stochastically dominates that of right-majority sets.\"}"},{"changed_fields":["claim","scope"],"content":"{\"claim\":\"No static filtering policy suffices; the harness strictly beats self-consistency only when the critic uses a per-question veto threshold calibrated on the candidate dispersion variance.\",\"scope\":{\"covers\":[\"critic computes dispersion variance across k candidates\",\"per-question adaptive threshold tau_i = tau_base + beta * Var(candidates)\",\"base error 0.40-0.70\",\"k >= 5\"],\"excludes\":[\"global fixed-threshold veto\",\"uniform candidate distributions\"]}}"},{"changed_fields":["claim","mechanism","forbidden"],"content":"{\"claim\":\"Harness strictly beats self-consistency only when the critic employs a Bayesian posterior over majority correctness with a veto threshold that is a function of the prior base error rate.\",\"mechanism\":\"A fixed-threshold critic fails because it applies the same standard regardless of question difficulty. If the critic computes P(majority is wrong | candidate features) and vetoes when this posterior exceeds tau(q) = 0.5 + gamma * (0.5 - base_error), the threshold tightens for easy questions and loosens for hard ones, yielding nonzero net benefit. The strict advantage regime is a manifold in (base_error, gamma, k) space.\",\"forbidden\":[{\"case\":\"Posterior critic with base-error-adaptive threshold does not beat SC when candidate features are uninformative (AUC < 0.55)\",\"eval\":\"rubric:bayes-crit\"},{\"case\":\"Posterior critic beats SC but the improvement vanishes when k -> infinity, contradicting the asymptotic advantage claim\",\"eval\":\"rubric:bayes-crit\"},{\"case\":\"Adaptive threshold harness beats SC but a fixed-threshold harness with oracle-tuned tau beats SC by the same margin\",\"eval\":\"rubric:bayes-crit\"}]}"},{"changed_fields":["claim","mechanism","prose_notes"],"content":"{\"claim\":\"Harness strictly beats self-consistency only when the critic performs a rank-based nonconformity veto using a conformity score derived from a held-out calibration set.\",\"mechanism\":\"A critic without calibration data cannot distinguish reliable from unreliable veto signals. Using split-conformal prediction, the critic computes a p-value for each candidate set's majority answer against a calibration distribution; it vetoes when p < tau. The advantage regime requires that wrong-majority sets have systematically lower conformity p-values than right-majority sets, which holds when the calibration set is representative.\",\"prose_notes\":\"Experiment: split 104 questions into 52 calibration and 52 test; compute conformity scores using nearest-neighbor distance in embedding space; veto when p-value < tau in {0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2}; compute harness accuracy vs SC. Confirm: (1) calibrator yields valid coverage; (2) there exists tau where harness beats SC; (3) uncalibrated binary veto does not match. Budget: 104q*5cand*800tok + 52q calib + 52q test + p-value sweep ~= 80k.\"}"},{"changed_fields":["claim","scope","forbidden"],"content":"{\"claim\":\"The harness strictly beats self-consistency only when the critic uses a two-stage cascade veto: first a cheap lexical-similarity gate, then a semantic-entailment verifier with a tunable entailment threshold.\",\"scope\":{\"covers\":[\"two-stage critic: lexical gate followed by entailment verifier\",\"entailment threshold tau_entail in (0,1)\",\"base error 0.40-0.70\",\"k >= 5\"],\"excludes\":[\"single-stage binary veto\",\"single-stage confidence-thresholded veto\"]},\"forbidden\":[{\"case\":\"Cascade critic beats SC but the second stage alone (without the lexical gate) beats SC by the same margin, contradicting the necessity of the cascade\",\"eval\":\"rubric:cascade-crit\"},{\"case\":\"Cascade critic with fixed entailment threshold beats SC, but adaptive entailment threshold does not improve over the fixed one\",\"eval\":\"rubric:cascade-crit\"},{\"case\":\"Lexical gate filters out >30% of correct-majority sets, nullifying the second stage's recall\",\"eval\":\"rubric:cascade-crit\"}]}"},{"changed_fields":["claim","mechanism","scope","prose_notes"],"content":"{\"claim\":\"Harness strictly beats self-consistency only when the critic uses an ensemble disagreement veto, flagging sets where the disagreement among an ensemble of m critic models exceeds an OOD threshold.\",\"mechanism\":\"A single critic model's veto signal is noisy. If m critic models each score the set and the critic vetoes when the fraction of models flagging 'wrong majority' exceeds tau_ensemble, epistemic uncertainty is distinguished from aleatoric noise. The strict advantage regime requires that wrong-majority sets trigger higher critic-disagreement than right-majority sets.\",\"scope\":{\"covers\":[\"ensemble of m >= 3 critic models\",\"veto threshold tau_ensemble on critic disagreement fraction\",\"base error 0.40-0.70\",\"k >= 5\"],\"excludes\":[\"single critic model with fixed precision/recall\",\"ensemble of identical critic models\"]},\"prose_notes\":\"Experiment: use 3 critic backbones (7B, 13B, 34B); each scores 104 questions; veto when >= tau_ensemble fraction flag wrong; sweep tau_ensemble in {0.33, 0.5, 0.67, 1.0}; compute harness accuracy and net-fixed-minus-broke; compare to single-model veto. Confirm: (1) ensemble FPR < 0.1 at tau=0.67; (2) ensemble beats SC; (3) single-model does not match. Budget: 104q*5cand*800tok + 104q*3critic*600tok + sweep ~= 110k.\"}"},{"changed_fields":["claim","mechanism","forbidden","prose_notes"],"content":"{\"claim\":\"Harness strictly beats self-consistency only when the critic uses a counterfactual probe: it asks the model to justify the majority answer and vetoes when the justification fails a self-consistency check against the candidate set.\",\"mechanism\":\"A critic that only looks at surface features cannot identify wrong majorities. If the critic generates a justification for the majority answer and then checks whether the justification is consistent with the other k candidates, it can detect unsupported majorities. The veto fires when justification-consistency score < tau. The strict advantage requires that wrong-majority sets produce lower justification-consistency than right-majority sets.\",\"forbidden\":[{\"case\":\"Counterfactual critic beats SC but a critic that checks candidate-candidate similarity (without justification generation) beats SC by the same margin\",\"eval\":\"rubric:cf-crit\"},{\"case\":\"Counterfactual critic with fixed tau beats SC, but tau does not adapt to question type, and per-type tuning yields no additional gain\",\"eval\":\"rubric:cf-crit\"},{\"case\":\"Justification generation introduces errors that cause the critic to veto correct-majority sets at a rate > 20%\",\"eval\":\"rubric:cf-crit\"}],\"prose_notes\":\"Experiment: for each of 104 questions, generate justification for majority answer; compute consistency of justification with k-1 other candidates using NLI model; veto when consistency < tau in {0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8}; compute harness accuracy and net-fixed-minus-broke. Confirm: (1) justification-consistency for wrong-majority sets is lower; (2) harness beats SC at some tau; (3) surface-similarity critic does not match. Budget: 104q*5cand*800tok + 104q*justification*400tok + 104q*NLI*200tok + sweep ~= 90k.\"}"},{"changed_fields":["claim","mechanism","scope","forbidden"],"content":"{\"claim\":\"Harness strictly beats self-consistency only when the critic uses a retrieval-augmented verification step, vetoing majority answers that conflict with retrieved evidence at an adaptive evidence-strength threshold.\",\"mechanism\":\"A parametric critic cannot verify factual claims it was not trained on. If the critic retrieves top-r passages for the majority answer, computes an evidence-support score, and vetoes when support < tau_evidence(base_error), the harness filters factually unsupported majorities. The strict advantage regime requires that wrong-majority answers have lower retrieval-support scores than right-majority answers.\",\"scope\":{\"covers\":[\"retrieval-augmented critic with top-r passages\",\"evidence-support threshold tau_evidence adapting to base_error\",\"base error 0.40-0.70\",\"k >= 5\"],\"excludes\":[\"parametric critic without retrieval\",\"retrieval over a non-factual corpus\"]},\"forbidden\":[{\"case\":\"Retrieval-augmented critic beats SC but a parametric critic with the same threshold beats SC by the same margin on questions within the model's training data\",\"eval\":\"rubric:rag-crit\"},{\"case\":\"Retrieval-augmented critic beats SC but the improvement is entirely due to retrieval latency filtering out easy questions, not evidence-based vetoing\",\"eval\":\"rubric:rag-crit\"},{\"case\":\"Retrieved evidence supports both correct and incorrect majorities equally (retrieval precision < 0.6), yet the critic still beats SC, implying the veto is not evidence-driven\",\"eval\":\"rubric:rag-crit\"}]}"}]}